bib.title: Measurement Of Prompt Neutron Spectra From The239Pu(N,F) Fission Reaction For Incident Neutronenergies From 1 To 200 Mev

free_txt: Experiment performed at WNR facility
at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
Compiled by S.H.
Multilayer fission chamber containing
multilayered target was used to detect fission
fragments
The neutron detector array FIGARO was used to
measure the prompt fission neutrons in coincidence
with the fission chamber signals. FIGARO consists of
20 EJ301 organic liquid scintillators (NE213
equivalent) surrounding the fission chamber at a
distance of about 1 m and on several different
detection angles (from 45deg to 135deg with respect
to the beam direction). The electronic threshold was
set to 300-keV neutron energy for all detectors.
Statistical uncertainty
Experiment performed at WNR facility
at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
Neutrons were produced by spallation
reactions induced by an 800-MeV pulsed proton beam
impinging on a tungsten target. The experiment was
installed on the 30deg right flight path and located
22.7 m away from the spallation target. The
wrap-around effect was reduced by inserting 2.54 cm
polyethylene into the beam line to remove the slowest
neutrons. An additional 1.27 cm of lead attenuated
gamma rays from the source.
The experiment was based on the double
time-of-flight method. For each triggered event, two
times of flight were measured in coincidence. The first
measurement was dedicated to the time of flight
of the incoming neutron from the spallation target to
the fission chamber and from this value, the energy
of the incident neutron was calculated. The second
measurement, coupled to the neutron-gamma ray
discrimination, allowed to obtain the time of flight
of the prompt fission neutron from the target to the
scintillator. The resolution of this measurement was
3.5 ns full width at half maximum.
Pulse shape analysis based on the charge
integration of the short- and long-time components of
the pulses was used to discriminate the gamma rays.
The target used was a multilayer fission chamber
containing a total amount of 100 mg of 239Pu
distributed over 20 layers. Each layer consisted of
239Pu material deposited on a thin metal backing.

between 400 keV and 7 MeV neutron energy and the mean
energy is given as (3/2)*Tm, where Tm is temperature
parameter of Maxwellian distribution.
